Date: 07 Nov 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Subject: Bone meal ban urged
Source: Reuters, 7 Nov 2000 [edited
<http://asia.dailynews.yahoo.com/headlines/world/article.html?s=asia/headlin
es/001107/world/afp/Chirac_calls_for_immediate_ban_on_bone_meal_in_animal_fe
ed.html>

President Jacques Chirac urged drastic new precautions against mad cow
disease (Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy, BSE) and a top health official
predicted more people would die as France's proud culinary tradition took a
hammering.
Chirac called on the government to suspend immediately the use of meat and
bone meal (MBM) in all animal feed amid growing anxiety about the spread of
BSE .
"With the rise in the number of cases of BSE in France, it is highly likely
that we will have dozens of cases of new variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease
(nvCJD). We must prepare for that," Gillot said.
Gillot's comments came as Paris, Bordeaux and other cities stripped beef
from school menus, bringing to over a dozen the number of municipalities
that have taken matters into their own hands.
The latest food scare, when several supermarket chains announced they had
sold beef potentially contaminated with BSE, has shattered consumer
confidence in a country where meat is at the heart of the dining experience.
It has also hit the reputation of French beef abroad, with several eastern
European countries slapping curbs or all-out bans on imports of its meat.
The bans hit all the harder for a country which has refused to lift its own
ban on British beef following an outbreak of BSE across the Channel.
The left-wing government, which has always said public health was
paramount, found itself under the gun following Chirac's call for a ban on
the use of MBM for all animals, not just cattle.
Farm Minister Jean Glavany said the country was losing its senses and there
was no question of banning beef or of banning all use of MBM until the
national food safety agency, AFFSA, had finished analysing the issue.
Chirac said the authorities should not wait the 3 or 4 months it could take
AFSSA to deliver a verdict and should instead act now to protect consumers
from the fatal, brain- wasting disease.
France has started reporting far more cases of BSE since the government
started tests in June to gauge the extent of the illness among its 21
million cattle.
France's farm ministry reported 3 new cases of BSE on Monday, bringing the
total this year to 89, nearly triple the 30 cases reported last year.
Most scientists are convinced eating contaminated beef is the most likely
mode of transmission of the disease from cattle to humans.
